headline: The Week in Numbers: big tech, smaller tariffs
summary:
STORY: From big tech to smaller tariffs, this is the The Week in Numbers. 

:: The Week in Numbers

:: $5 trillion

A $5 trillion market valuation saw Nvidia make history as the first company to reach the eye watering valuation. 

It was powered by a rally that has cemented its place at the center of the global artificial intelligence boom.

The milestone underscores the swift transformation from a niche graphics-chip designer into the backbone of the global AI industry.

Nvidia stock has surged 50% this year.

:: 47%

47% is the new U.S. tariff on China, down from 57%.

President Trump said that he had struck a deal with Chinese President Xi Jinping to reduce the levies. 

That is in exchange for Beijing resuming U.S. soybean purchases, keeping rare earth exports flowing and cracking down on the illicit trade of fentanyl.

Trump spoke to reporters aboard Air Force One: 

“I think pretty soon we have not too many major stumbling blocks. We were, we have a deal, now. Every year we'll renegotiate the deal."

:: $1 trillion

$1 trillion could be the valuation sought by OpenAI.

It's reportedly laying the groundwork for one of the biggest IPOs of all time.

Three people familiar with the matter said the ChatGPT-maker is seeking to raise at least $60 billion.

But they say talks are at an early stage, and plans could still change.

:: 14%

14% is the amount Amazon shares surged by in after hours trading. 

It followed the news that cloud revenue rose at the fastest clip in nearly three years, helping the company forecast quarterly sales above estimates.

And adding $330 billion to its market value. 

This week Amazon announced a cut of 14,000 corporate jobs in a major shakeup driven by artificial intelligence.

:: $5.8 billion

A $5.8 billion tariff hit for Volkswagen resulted in a hefty blow for its third quarter results. 

Resulting in a $1.5 billion operating loss.

The carmaker was also dealing with an expensive course correction at subsidiary Porsche.

It booked billions of dollars in charges due to Porsche's strategy reversal on electric vehicles.

headline: Samsung in talks with Nvidia to supply advanced HBM4 chips
summary:
STORY: :: Samsung

Samsung Electronics said Friday it’s in “close” talks to supply its next-generation AI chips to Nvidia. 

That’s as the South Korean tech giant struggles to catch up with rivals in the AI chip race. 

These new high-bandwidth memory chips - or HBM4 - are a key building block of artificial intelligence infrastructure. 

And Samsung plans to market its version of the advanced chip next year - but didn’t give a shipping date.  

:: SK Hynix

Local rival SK Hynix, Nvidia's top HBM chip supplier, on Wednesday said it aims to start shipping its HBM4 chips in the fourth quarter and expand sales next year.

AI tech giant Nvidia confirmed a “key supply collaboration” with Samsung but didn’t elaborate. 

:: Nvidia

In a separate deal, Samsung said it will purchase 50,000 high-end Nvidia chips.

That’s to build an AI-enhanced semiconductor factory aimed at improving manufacturing speed and yields.

Samsung's share price hit highs of around 4.3% after the announcements.

headline: Nvidia to supply more than 260,000 Blackwell AI chips to South Korea
summary: SEOUL/GYEONGJU (Reuters) -U.S. semiconductor leader Nvidia on Friday said it will supply more than 260,000 of its most advanced AI chips to South Korea's government and some of the country's biggest businesses, including Samsung Electronics.  For Korea, the deal will put the country on track to become a regional AI hub after President Lee Jae Myung, who took office on June 4, prioritised AI investment to spur growth at a time when U.S. tariffs have clouded the broader economic outlook.  "Just as Korea's physical factories have inspired the world with sophisticated ships, cars, chips and electronics, the nation can now produce intelligence as a new export that will drive global transformation," Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang said in a statement, disclosing neither deal value nor supply schedule.

headline: Samsung Electronics in talks with Nvidia to supply next-generation HBM4 chips
summary: SEOUL (Reuters) -Samsung Electronics said on Friday it is in "close discussion" to supply its next-generation high-bandwidth memory (HBM) chips, or HBM4, to Nvidia, as the South Korean chipmaker scrambles to catch up with rivals in the AI chip race.  Samsung, which plans to market the new chip next year, did not specify when it aims to ship the latest version of its HBM chip, a key building block of artificial intelligence chipsets.  Local rival SK Hynix, Nvidia's top HBM chip supplier, on Wednesday said it aims to start shipping its latest HBM4 chips in the fourth quarter and expand sales next year.
